data.content:
Yes! Two better options:

**1. `[DataRow]` — simplest for inline constants:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

**2. Strongly-typed `DynamicData` (MSTest v3+) — best when you need computed/complex data:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData<string, bool>(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string, bool)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**Use `[DataRow]`** when all values are compile-time constants. **Use generic `DynamicData<T1, T2>`** when you need runtime-generated data — it gives you type safety without the `object[]` casts.
